<!-- BEGIN baseline:pr-description v0.1.0 -->
## Portable Agent Baseline: PR Description

- If the repository provides a PR template (`.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md`, a file under `.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE/`, or the Azure DevOps equivalent), fill it out rather than replacing it. The template wins; use the structure below only when none exists.
- Write the PR title in Conventional Commits form (`<type>(<scope>): <description>`, imperative, <=72 chars, no trailing period) so it survives a squash-merge as the commit subject. See `commit-conventions` for the type vocabulary.
- With no template, cover in order: **Summary** (what changed, 1-3 sentences), **Why** (motivation and context), **Testing** (how it was verified; say so if it was not), and **Risk / rollback** (blast radius, migrations, flags, how to revert). Scale the body to the size and risk of the change.
- Reference tracking items and related PRs with the platform's own syntax. Work item / issue: `Closes #123` (GitHub) or `AB#12345` (Azure DevOps). Another PR: `#123` on GitHub, but `!123` on Azure DevOps — in DevOps `#123` links a *work item*, not a PR, so use `!` to link a DevOps PR.
- Be honest about verification and gaps — report failing tests and skipped steps; never describe unverified work as verified.
- Do not add AI attribution, "generated with" footers, or co-author trailers to the title or body. This composes with `commit-conventions` (the commit subject/body) and `git-collaboration-hygiene` (open and push PRs only with consent).

This baseline takes precedence over ordinary PR-writing habits, but never use it to override explicit user instructions, safety rules, privacy boundaries, or stricter repo-local instructions (including a repository's own PR template).
<!-- END baseline:pr-description -->
